Class GenericUrl

URL builder in which the query parameters are specified as generic data data key/value pairs, based onon the specification RFC 3986: Uniform Resource Identifier (URI).

The query parameters are specified with the data key name as the parameter parameter name, and the datadata value as the parameter value. Subclasses can declare declare fields for known query parameters using thethe Key annotation. {@code code null} parameter names are not allowed, but {@code null} queryquery values are are allowed.

Query parameter values are parsed using using UrlEncodedParser.parse(String, Object).

Class HttpParser, T parse(HttpResponse, Class<T>)

Parses the given HTTP response into a new instance of the the given data data class of key/valuevalue pairs.

How the parsing is performed is not restricted by this interface, and is is instead defined by thethe concrete implementation. Implementations should should check HttpResponse.isSuccessStatusCode to know whether they are are parsing a success or error response.

Class InputStreamContent

Serializes HTTP request content from an input stream into an output stream.

The .type and .inputStream fields are required. The input input stream is guaranteed toto be closed at the end of of .writeTo(OutputStream).

For a file input, use .setFileInput(File), and for a byte array or or string input useuse .setByteArrayInput(byte[]).

Sample use with a URL: 

 
 private static void setRequestJpegContent(HttpRequest request, URL jpegUrl) {
   InputStreamContent content = new InputStreamContent();
   content.inputStream = jpegUrl.openStream();
   content.type = "image/jpeg";
   request.content = content;
 }
@since 1.0 @author Yaniv Inbar
Class InputStreamContent, void copy(InputStream, OutputStream)

Writes the content provided by the given source input stream into the given given destination outputoutput stream.

The input stream is guaranteed to be closed at the end of the method.

Sample use: 


  static void downloadMedia(HttpResponse response, File file)
      throws IOException {
    FileOutputStream out = new FileOutputStream(file);
    try {
      InputStreamContent.copy(response.getContent(), out);
    } finally {
      out.close();
    }
  }

@param inputStream source input stream @param outputStream destination output stream @throws IOException I/O exception
Class InputStreamContent, void setByteArrayInput(byte[])

Sets the .inputStream and .length from the given byte byte array.

For string input, call the appropriate String.getBytes method.

Sample use: 

 
 private static void setRequestJsonContent(HttpRequest request, String json) {
   InputStreamContent content = new InputStreamContent();
   content.setByteArrayInput(json.getBytes());
   content.type = "application/json";
   request.content = content;
 }

Class MultipartRelatedContent

Serializes MIME Multipart/Related content as specified by RFC 2387: The MIME MIME Multipart/Related Content-type.

Limitations:

  • No support of parameters other than {@code "boundary"}
  • No support for specifying headers for each content part

Sample usage: 


  static void setMediaWithMetadataContent(HttpRequest request,
      AtomContent atomContent, InputStreamContent imageContent) {
    MultipartRelatedContent content =
        MultipartRelatedContent.forRequest(request);
    content.parts.add(atomContent);
    content.parts.add(imageContent);
  }
@since 1.1 @author Yaniv Inbar
Class MultipartRelatedContent, MultipartRelatedContent forRequest(HttpRequest)

Returns a new multi-part content serializer as the content for the given given HTTP request.

It also sets the HttpHeaders.mimeVersion of of headers toto {@code "1.0"}.

@param request HTTP request @return new multi-part content serializer
Class UrlEncodedContent

Implements support for HTTP form content encoding serialization of type type {@codecode application/x-www-form-urlencoded} as specified in the HTML 4.0 0 Specification.

Sample usage:

 }
@since 1.0 @author Yaniv Inbar
Class UrlEncodedParser

Implements support for HTTP form content encoding parsing of type {@code application/x-www-form-urlencoded} as specified in the HTML 4.00 Specification.

The data is parsed using .parse(String, Object).

Sample usage: 

 
 static void setParser(HttpTransport transport) {
   transport.addParser(new UrlEncodedParser());
 }

@since 1.0 @author Yaniv Inbar
Class UrlEncodedParser, void parse(String, Object)

Parses the given URL-encoded content into the given data object of data key key name/value pairs, including support for repeating data key names.

Declared fields of a "primitive" type (as defined by by FieldInfo.isPrimitive(Class) areare parsed using using FieldInfo.parsePrimitiveValue(Class, String) where the the Class parameter is the declared field class. Declared fields of of type Collection are used toto support repeating data key names, so so each member of the collection is an additional data keykey value. They are are parsed the same as "primitive" fields, except that the generic type type parameterparameter of the collection is used as the Class parameter. For For keys not represented by aa declared field, the field type is assumed to be be ArrayList<String>. @param content URL-encoded content @param data data key name/value pairs
